</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.LC.S16-5" type="ext"/>[LCA07 s 16.5 ] </edpnum><title>Validity of the appointment of Acting Judicial Officers</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>This issue has been considered in relation to Supreme Court and District Court judicial officers.  In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="2006"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr000098" spanref="cr000098-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="228"/><ci:page num="45"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000099" spanref="cr000099-002"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="229"/><ci:page num="223"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr000100" spanref="cr000100-003"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200606891"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000100" spanref="cr000100-004"><ci:pinpoint num="102" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Forge v Australian Securities and Investments Commission</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr000098-001" status="unval">(2006) 228 CLR 45</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr000099-002">229 ALR 223</ci:span>; [2006] HCA 44; <ci:span spanid="cr000100-003"> BC200606891</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000100-004">at [102]</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="423079" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>, the High Court rejected an argument that the appointment of acting judges to the Supreme Court of NSW was invalid because it compromised the institutional integrity of the Court as a body required to exercise federal judicial power, and as recognized by the Constitution.  However, the Court acknowledged that the appointment of acting judges, who lacked tenure and hence independence, could impugn the institutional integrity of the (Supreme) Court: Forge v Australian Securities and Investments Commission, above, <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000101" spanref="cr000101-000" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="HCA"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="2006"/></ci:edition><ci:pinpoint num="101" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"><ci:span spanid="cr000101-000" status="unval">at [101]</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> per Gummow, Hayne and Crennan JJ.</text></p>
<p>
<text>In relation to Acting Judges of the District Court, the Supreme Court opined that it was fanciful to think that an informed observer would view the volume of the Court&#x2019;s caseload undertaken by acting judges in 2009 and 2010 as diminishing the status of the Court as a body comprised almost entirely of permanent judicial officers: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr000102" spanref="cr000102-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC201006774"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr000102" spanref="cr000102-002"><ci:pinpoint num="84" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Downey v Acting District Court Judge Boulton (No 5)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2010] NSWCA 240; <ci:span spanid="cr000102-001"> BC201006774</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr000102-002">at [84]</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="503043" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> ff.  The case concerned the continuation in office of an acting District Court Judge who had turned, or was about to turn, 75 during his continuation of the hearing of a case beyond that time.  The court found that there were valid grounds to suggest that the judge was continuing to hear the substantive case (an appeal), the hearing of which had not concluded, thereby entitling him to continue the hearing of the matter under District Court Act 1973 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.DC.DCAN.S18.3A" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">s 18(3A)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
, couched in similar terms to Local Court Act 2007 Sch 1 Pt 4 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.LC.LCAN07.SCH1.CL12.2" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">cl 12(2)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
.</text></p>
